"1090":"1090","1145":"1145","Abt 1104":"circa 1104","1130":"1130","1170":"1170","Ruthven, Angus, Scotland":"Ruthven, Angus, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","OF, RUTHVEN, PERTH, SCOTLAND":"Ruthven, Perthshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1090–1145":"1090–1145","–Female":"Deceased","1130–1170":"1130–1170","1090":"1090","1145":"1145","Abt 1104":"about 1104","1130":"1130","1170":"1170","Ruthven, Angus, Scotland":"Ruthven, Angus, Scotland, United Kingdom","OF, RUTHVEN, PERTH, SCOTLAND":"Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Sweyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish and Scottish: shortened form of   McSween  .","Norwegian: variant of   Sveen  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McSween","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Suibhne</b>, ‘son of <i>Suibhne</i>’, a Gaelic name meaning ‘pleasant, affable’, see   McQueen   1 and Irish   McSweeney  .","Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Suain</b> based on Old Norse <i>sveinn</i> ‘boy, servant’, which was also used as a personal name. This is given as the origin of the   McQueen   family of Skye (see also   McSwain   and   Whan  ) although the two similar personal names <i>Suibhne</i> and <i>Sveinn</i>, Gaelic and Scandinavian, have influenced each other more widely in Scotland."]},{"name":"Sweeden","meanings":["Dutch (<b>Van Sweeden</b>): variant of <b>Van Zweeden</b>, a habitational name for someone from Sweden.","Probably also an altered form of Norwegian   Sween   or possibly Irish   Sweeten  , or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ruthven","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name, traditionally pronounced ‘Ri-ven’, from Ruthven by Huntingtower (Perthshire); also possibly from Ruthven (Angus) and various other places of that name throughout Scotland, named either with Gaelic <i>ruadh</i> ‘red’ + <i>mhaighin</i> ‘place’ or with a cognate of Welsh <i>rhudd faen</i> ‘red stone’. The oldest family of this name, the lords of the barony of Ruthven by Perth, were descended from Thor, son of Swain, lord of Tranent in Lothian and first sheriff of Edinburgh on record in the mid 12th century. The family eventually gained the title of Earl of Gowrie, but because of what became known as ‘the Gowrie Conspiracy’ the title was forfeited and from 1600 to 1641 the surname itself was proscribed. The title was later restored to the family, and the present Earl of Gowrie bears the surname <i>Ruthven</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sweyn of Ruthven was born in 1090. He married Lady Sweyn Ruthven about 1104, in Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1145, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1090–1145":"1090–1145","–Female":"Surnud","1130–1170":"1130–1170","1090":"1090","1145":"1145","Abt 1104":"umbes 1104","1130":"1130","1170":"1170","Ruthven, Angus, Scotland":"Ruthven, Angus, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","OF, RUTHVEN, PERTH, SCOTLAND":"Ruthven, Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1090–1145":"1090–1145","–Female":"Kuollut","1130–1170":"1130–1170","1090":"1090","1145":"1145","Abt 1104":"noin 1104","1130":"1130","1170":"1170","Ruthven, Angus, Scotland":"Ruthven, Angus, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","OF, RUTHVEN, PERTH, SCOTLAND":"Ruthven, Perthshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1090–1145":"1090–1145","–Female":"Décédée","1130–1170":"1130–1170","1090":"1090","1145":"1145","Abt 1104":"environ 1104","1130":"1130","1170":"1170","Ruthven, Angus, Scotland":"Ruthven, Angus, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","OF, RUTHVEN, PERTH, SCOTLAND":"Ruthven, Pert